{"title_page": "List of Spanish-language television networks in the United States", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Latinos in the United States}}\nThe following is a list of [[Spanish language in the United States|Spanish-language]] [[television in the United States|television]] [[Television network|networks]] in the United States. As of 2016 the largest Hispanic/Latino television [[media market|audiences]] in the U.S. are in California (Los Angeles, San Francisco area), New York, Florida (Miami area), Texas (Houston, Dallas, Ft. Worth, San Antonio), Illinois (Chicago), and Arizona (Phoenix).<ref>{{cite web |title=Local Television Market Universe Estimates: Hispanic or Latino TV Homes |date= September 2016 |author=[[Nielsen Company]] |url=https://www.tvb.org/Public/Research/Measurement/NielsenDMARanks.aspx |via=[[Television Bureau of Advertising|Television Bureau of Advertising, Inc.]] }}</ref>\n\n==Major networks==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! TV network\n! Founded\n! Owner\n! % of U.S. households reached\n! # of households viewable\n! # of [[List of broadcast station classes#Full-Service Stations|Full-power]] [[Network affiliate|affiliates]]\n! # of [[Low-power broadcasting#Television|Low-power]]/[[Class A television service|Class-A]] affiliates and transmitters\n|-\n| [[Univision]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1987<ref>Date at which the [[Spanish International Network]] (founded in 1962) was reorganized and became Univision.</ref>\n| [[Univision Communications]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 49%\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 94,100,000<ref>{{cite news|title=Univision Network|url=http://corporate.univision.com/media-property/univision-network/|author=Univision|publisher=Univision Corporate|accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 62\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 26\n|-\n| [[Estrella TV]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2009\n| [[Liberman Broadcasting]]<br><small>(alternatively referred