ermococcus sp. Tc-4-85|T. sp. Tc-4-85]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc70-CRC-I|T. sp. Tc70-CRC-I]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc70-CRC-S|T. sp. Tc70-CRC-S]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc70-MC-S|T. sp. Tc70-MC-S]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc70-SC-I|T. sp. Tc70-SC-I]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc70-SC-S|T. sp. Tc70-SC-S]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc85-0 age SC|T. sp. Tc85-0 age SC]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc85-CRC-I|T. sp. Tc85-CRC-I]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc85-CRC-S|T. sp. Tc85-CRC-S]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc85-MC-I|T. sp. Tc85-MC-I]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc85-MC-S|T. sp. Tc85-MC-S]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc85-SC-ISCS|T. sp. Tc85-SC-ISCS]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc85-SC-I|T. sp. Tc85-SC-I]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc85-SC-S|T. sp. Tc85-SC-S]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc95-CRC-I|T. sp. Tc95-CRC-I]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc95-CRC-S|T. sp. Tc95-CRC-S]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc95-MC-I|T. sp. Tc95-MC-I]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc95-MC-S|T. sp. Tc95-MC-S]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc95-SC-S|T. sp. Tc95-SC-S]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc-I-70|T. sp. Tc-I-70]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc-I-85|T. sp. Tc-I-85]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc-S-70|T. sp. Tc-S-70]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. Tc-S-85|T. sp. Tc-S-85]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. TK1|T. sp. TK1]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. TM1|T. sp. TM1]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. TS2|T. sp. TS2]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. TS3|T. sp. TS3]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus sp. vp197|T. sp. vp197]]''\n* ''[[Thermococcus stetteri|T. stetteri]]''\n* ''T. waimanguensis''\n* ''T. waiotapuensis''\n* ''T. zilligii''\n* Uncultured ''Thermococcus'' sp.]]\n| synonyms =\n}}\n\nIn [[alpha taxonomy|taxonomy]], '''''Thermococcus''''' is a [[genus (biology)|genus]] of extreme [[thermophile]]s in the family the [[Thermococcaceae]].<ref>See the [[National Center for Biotechnology Information|NCBI]] [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Taxonomy/Browser/wwwtax.cgi?mode=Info&id=2263 webpage on Thermococcus].  Data extracted from the {{cite web | url=ftp://ftp.ncbi.nih.gov/pub/taxonomy/ | title=NCBI taxonomy resources | publisher=[[National Center for Biotechnology Information]] | accessdate=2007-03-19}}</ref>\n\nMembers of the genus ''Thermococcus'' are all [[Archaea]], having thermophillic-hyperthermophillic characteristics.<ref name=\"one\">{{cite journal | last1 = Amenabar | first1 = M. J. |display-authors=etal | year = 2013 | title = Archaeal diversity from hydrothermal systems of Deception Island, Antarctica | url = | journal = Polar Biology | volume = 36 | issue = 3| pages = 373\u2013380 | doi=10.1007/s00300-012-1267-3}}</ref> These microorganisms are typically irregularly shaped coccoid species, ranging in size from 0.6-2.0 \u03bcm in diameter.<ref name=\"two\">{{cite journal | last1 =  Canganella | first1 = Francesco | last2 = Jones | first2 = William J. | last3 = Gambacorta | first3 = Agata | last4 = Antranikian | first4 = Garabed | year = 1998 | title = ''Thermococcus guaymasensis'' sp. nov. and ''Thermococcus aggregans'' sp. nov., two novel thermophilic archaea isolated from the Guaymas Basin hydrothermal vent site | url = | journal = International Journal of Systematic Bacteriology | volume = 48 | issue = 4| page = 6 | doi = 10.1099/00207713-48-4-1181 | doi-access = free }}</ref> Some species of ''Thermococcus'' are immobile, and some species have motility, using flagella as their main mode of movement.<ref name=\"one\" /><ref name=\"two\" /><ref name=\"three\">{{cite journal | last1 = Schut | first1 = G. J. |display-authors=etal | year = 2013 | title = The modular respiratory complexes involved in hydrogen and sulfur metabolism by heterotrophic hyperthermophilic archaea and their evolutionary implications | url = | journal = FEMS Microbiology Reviews | volume = 37 | issue = 2| pages = 182\u2013203 | doi=10.1111/j.1574-6976.2012.00346.x| doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"four\">Yuusuke Tokooji, T. S., Shinsuke Fujiwara, Tadayuki Imanaka and Haruyuki Atomi (2013). \"Genetic Examination of Initial Amino Acid Oxidation and Glutamate Catabolism in the Hyperthermophilic Archaeon ''Thermococcus kodakarensis''.\" ''Journal of Bacteriology'': 10.</ref><ref name=\"five\">{{cite journal | last1 = Bezsudnova | first1 = E. Y. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Structural insight into the molecular basis of polyextremophilicity of short-chain alcohol dehydrogenase from the hyperthermophilic archaeon ''Thermococcus sibiricus'' | url = | journal = Biochimie | volume = 94 | issue = 12| pages = 2628\u20132638 | doi=10.1016/j.biochi.2012.07.024}}</ref><ref name=\"six\">{{cite journal | last1 = Cho | first1 = S. S. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Characterization and PCR application of a new high-fidelity DNA polymerase from ''Thermococcus waiotapuensis'' | url = | journal = Enzyme and Microbial Technology | volume = 51 | issue = 6\u20137| pages = 334\u2013341 | doi=10.1016/j.enzmictec.2012.07.017}}</ref><ref name=\"seven\">{{cite journal | last1 = Atomi | first1 = H. |display-authors=etal | year = 2013 | title = CoA biosynthesis in archaea | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/88b9a37b541a9b318a4d0c7a16ff6d40609f5715| journal = Biochemical Society Transactions | volume = 41 | issue = | pages = 427\u2013431 | doi=10.1042/bst20120311}}</ref><ref name=\"eight\">{{cite journal | last1 = Lee | first1 = J. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Hydrogen production from C1 compounds by a novel marine hyperthermophilic archaeon ''Thermococcus onnurineus'' NA1 | url = | journal = International Journal of Hydrogen Energy | volume = 37 | issue = 15| pages = 11113\u201311121 | doi=10.1016/j.ijhydene.2012.04.152}}</ref><ref name=\"nine\">{{cite journal | last1 = Aono | first1 = R. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Enzymatic Characterization of AMP Phosphorylase and Ribose-1,5-Bisphosphate Isomerase Functioning in an Archaeal AMP Metabolic Pathway | url = http://repository.kulib.kyoto-u.ac.jp/dspace/bitstream/2433/176910/1/JB.01335-12.pdf| journal = Journal of Bacteriology | volume = 194 | issue = 24| pages = 6847\u20136855 | doi=10.1128/jb.01335-12| pmid = 23065974 | pmc = 3510611 }}</ref><ref name=\"ten\">Jaime Andres Rivas-Pardo, A. H.-M., Victor Castro-Fernandez, Francisco J. Fernandez, M. \tCristina Vega, and Victoria Guixe (2013). \"Crystal Structure, SAXS and Kinetic Mechanism of Hyperthermophilic ADP-Depended Glucokinase from ''Thermococcus \tlitoralis'' Reveal a Conserved Mechanism for Catalysis \" ''PLoS ONE'' 12.</ref><ref name=\"eleven\">{{cite journal | last1 = Rogatykh | first1 = S. V. |display-authors=etal | year = 2013 | title = Evaluation of Quantitative and Qualitative Composition of Cultivated Acidophilic Microorganisms by Real-Time PCR and Clone Library Analysis | url = | journal = Microbiology | volume = 82 | issue = 2| pages = 210\u2013214 | doi=10.1134/s002626171301013x}}</ref><ref name=\"twelve\">Tae-Yang Jung, Y.-S. K., Byoung-Ha Oh, and Euijeon Woo (2012). \"Identification of a novel ligand binding site in phosphoserine phosphatase from the hyperthermophilic archaeon ''Thermococcus onnurineus''.\" Wiley Periodicals: 11.</ref> These flagella typically exist at a specific pole of the organism.<ref name=\"twelve\" /> This movement has been seen at room  or at high temperatures, depending on the specific organism.<ref name=\"thirteen\">{{cite journal | last1 = Tagashira | first1 = K. |display-authors=etal | year = 2013 | title = Genetic studies on the virus-like regions in the genome of hyperthermophilic archaeon, ''Thermococcus kodakarensis'' | url = | journal = Extremophiles | volume = 17 | issue = 1| pages = 153\u2013160 | doi=10.1007/s00792-012-0504-6}}</ref> In some species, these microorganisms can aggregate and form white-gray plaques,<ref name=\"twelve\" /> while all of these organisms dwell in temperatures from 70 to more than 100\u00b0C,<ref name=\"one\" /><ref name=\"two\" /><ref name=\"three\" /><ref name=\"four\" /><ref name=\"six\" /><ref name=\"seven\" /><ref name=\"eight\" /><ref name=\"nine\" /><ref name=\"ten\" /><ref name=\"eleven\" /><ref name=\"twelve\" /><ref name=\"thirteen\" /><ref name=\"fourteen\">{{cite journal | last1 = Gorlas | first1 = A. | last2 = Geslin | first2 = C. | year = 2013 | title = A simple procedure to determine the infectivity and host range of viruses infecting anaerobic and hyperthermophilic microorganisms | url = | journal = Extremophiles | volume = 17 | issue = 2| pages = 349\u2013355 | doi=10.1007/s00792-013-0513-0}}</ref><ref name=\"fifteen\">{{cite journal | last1 = Krupovic | first1 = M. |display-authors=etal | year = 2013 | title = Insights into Dynamics of Mobile Genetic Elements in Hyperthermophilic Environments from Five New ''Thermococcus'' Plasmids | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0049044 | pmid = 23326305 | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 8 | issue = 1 | page=e49044| pmc = 3543421 }}</ref><ref name=\"sixteen\">{{cite journal | last1 = Adrian Hetzer | first1 = H. W. M. | last2 = McDonald | first2 = Ian R. | last3 = Daughney | first3 = Christopher J. | year = 2007 | title = Microbial life in Champagne Pool, a geothermal spring in Waiotapu, New Zealand | url = | journal = Extremophiles | volume = 11 | issue = 4| pages = 605\u201314 | doi=10.1007/s00792-007-0073-2| pmid = 17426919 }}</ref><ref name=\"seventeen\">{{cite journal | last1 = Tomohiro Kato | first1 = X. L. | last2 = Asanuma | first2 = Hiroyuki | year = 2012 | title = Model of Elongation of Short DNA Sequence by Thermophilic DNA Polymerase under Isothermal Conditions | doi = 10.1021/bi3010413 | pmid = 22992125 | journal = Biochemistry | volume = 51 | issue = 40| page = 8 }}</ref><ref name=\"eighteen\">{{cite journal | last1 = Kim | first1 = B. K. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Genome Sequence of an Oligohaline Hyperthermophilic Archaeon, Thermococcus zilligii AN1, Isolated from a Terrestrial Geothermal Freshwater Spring | url = | journal = Journal of Bacteriology | volume = 194 | issue = 14| pages = 3765\u20133766 | doi=10.1128/jb.00655-12| pmid = 22740682 | pmc = 3393502 }}</ref><ref name=\"nineteen\">{{cite journal | last1 = Annmarie Neumer | first1 = H. W. J. | last2 = Belkin | first2 = Shimshon | last3 = Stetter | first3 = Karl O. |authorlink3= Karl Stetter| year = 1990 | title = ''Thermococcus litoralis'' sp. nov.: A new species of extremely thermophilic marine archaebacteria | url = | journal = Arch Microbiology | volume = 153 | issue = 1| page = 3 }}</ref><ref name=\"twenty\">{{cite journal | last1 = Holden | first1 = James F. | last2 = Summit | first2 = Melanie | last3 = Bolton | first3 = Sheryl | last4 = Zyskowski | first4 = Jamie | last5 = Baross | first5 = John A. | year = 2000 | title = Diversity among three novel groups of hyperthermophilic deep-sea ''Thermococcus'' species from three sites in the northeastern Pacific Ocean | doi = 10.1016/s0168-6496(01)00118-0 | journal = FEMS Microbiology Ecology | volume = 36 | issue = | page = 10 | doi-access = free }}</ref> either in the presence of black smokers (hydrothermal vents), or freshwater springs,<ref name=\"twentysix\">{{cite journal | last1 = Elisabeth Antoine | first1 = J. G. | last2 = Meunier | first2 = J. R. | last3 = Lesongeur | first3 = F. | last4 = Barbier | first4 = G. | year = 1995 | title = Isolation and Characterization of Extremely Thermophilic Archaebacteria Related to the Genus ''Thermococcus'' from Deep-Sea Hydrothermal Guaymas Basin | doi = 10.1007/bf00293552 | journal = Current Microbiology | volume = 31 | issue = 3| page = 7 }}</ref>  amongst salt (NaCl) concentrations of 1%-3%.<ref name=\"eighteen\" /> Species in this genus are strictly anaerobes,<ref name=\"one\" /><ref name=\"two\" /><ref name=\"three\" /><ref name=\"four\" /><ref name=\"five\" /><ref name=\"six\" /><ref name=\"seven\" /><ref name=\"eight\" /><ref name=\"nine\" /><ref name=\"ten\" /><ref name=\"eleven\" /><ref name=\"twelve\" /><ref name=\"thirteen\" /><ref name=\"fourteen\" /><ref name=\"fifteen\" /><ref name=\"sixteen\" /><ref name=\"seventeen\" /><ref name=\"eighteen\" /><ref name=\"nineteen\" /><ref name=\"twenty\" /> and  most are barophiles, as well as thermophiles,<ref name=\"one\" /><ref name=\"two\" /><ref name=\"three\" /><ref name=\"four\" /><ref name=\"five\" /><ref name=\"six\" /><ref name=\"seven\" /> living in depths between 200-<1000&nbsp;ft.<ref name=\"ten\" /><ref name=\"eleven\" /><ref name=\"twelve\" /><ref name=\"thirteen\" /><ref name=\"fourteen\" /><ref name=\"fifteen\" /><ref name=\"sixteen\" /><ref name=\"seventeen\" /><ref name=\"eighteen\" /><ref name=\"nineteen\" /><ref name=\"twenty\" /> These organisms thrive at pH levels of 5.6-7.9.<ref name=\"twentyone\">{{cite journal | last1 = Kazuo Tori | first1 = S. I. | authorlink4 = Yoshizumi Ishino | last2 = Kiyonari | first2 = Shinichi | last3 = Tahara | first3 = Saki | last4 = Ishino | first4 = Yoshizumi | year = 2013 | title = A Novel Single-Strand Specific 3'-5' Exonuclease Found in the Hyperthermophilic Archaeon, Pyrococcus furiosus | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0058497 | pmid = 23505520 | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 8 | issue = 3| page = 9 | pmc = 3591345 }}</ref> Members of this genus have been found in many hydrothermal vent systems in the world, including from the seas of Japan,<ref name=\"twentytwo\">{{cite journal | last1 = Cui | first1 = Z. C. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = High level expression and characterization of a thermostable lysophospholipase from ''Thermococcus kodakarensis'' KOD1 | url = | journal = Extremophiles | volume = 16 | issue = 4| pages = 619\u2013625 | doi=10.1007/s00792-012-0461-0| pmid = 22622648 }}</ref> to off the coasts of California.<ref name=\"twentythree\">{{cite journal | last1 = Uehara | first1 = Ryo | last2 = Takano | first2 = Kazufumi | last3 = Koga | first3 = Yuichi | last4 = Kanaya | first4 = Shigenori | year = 2012 | title = Requirement of insertion sequence IS1 for thermal adaptation of Pro-Tk-subtilisin from hyperthermophilic archaeon | doi = 10.1007/s00792-012-0479-3 | journal = Extremophiles | volume = 16 | issue = 6| page = 841 }}</ref> Surprisingly salt (NaCl) is not a required substrate for these organisms,<ref name=\"twentyfour\">{{cite journal | last1 = Cubonova | first1 = L. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = An Archaeal Histone Is Required for Transformation of ''Thermococcus kodakarensis'' | url = | journal = Journal of Bacteriology | volume = 194 | issue = 24| pages = 6864\u20136874 | doi=10.1128/jb.01523-12| pmid = 23065975 | pmc = 3510624 }}</ref><ref name=\"twentyfive\">{{cite journal | last1 = Anne Postec | first1 = F. L. | last2 = Pignet | first2 = Patricia | last3 = Ollivier | first3 = Bernard | last4 = Querellou | first4 = Joel | last5 = Godfroy | first5 = Anne | year = 2007 | title = Continuous enrichment cultures: insights into prokaryotic diversity and metabolic interactions in deep-sea vent chimneys | doi = 10.1007/s00792-007-0092-z | pmid = 17576518 | journal = Extremophiles | volume = 11 | issue = 6| page = 747 | url = https://archimer.ifremer.fr/doc/2007/publication-3885.pdf }}</ref> as one study showed ''Thermococcus'' members living in fresh hot water systems in New Zealand,<ref name=\"twentysix\" /> but they do require a low concentration of lithium ions for growth.<ref name=\"twentyseven\">{{cite journal | last1 = Eberly | first1 = Jed O. | year = 2008 | title = Thermotolerant Hydrogenases: Biological Diversity, Properties, and Biotechnological Applications | doi = 10.1080/10408410802240893 | pmid = 18728989 | journal = Critical Reviews in Microbiology | volume = 34 | issue = 3\u20134| pages = 117\u201330 }}</ref> ''Thermococcus'' members are described as heterotrophic, chemotrophic<ref name=\"one\" /><ref name=\"two\" /><ref name=\"three\" /><ref name=\"four\" /> and organotrophic sulfanogens;<ref name=\"one\" /><ref name=\"two\" /><ref name=\"three\" /><ref name=\"four\" /><ref name=\"five\" /><ref name=\"six\" /><ref name=\"seven\" /><ref name=\"eight\" /><ref name=\"nine\" /><ref name=\"ten\" /><ref name=\"eleven\" /><ref name=\"twelve\" /><ref name=\"thirteen\" /><ref name=\"fourteen\" /><ref name=\"fifteen\" /><ref name=\"sixteen\" /><ref name=\"seventeen\" /><ref name=\"eighteen\" /><ref name=\"nineteen\" /><ref name=\"twenty\" /> using elemental sulfur (S) and carbon sources including amino acids, carbohydrates, and organic acids such as pyruvate.<ref name=\"twentyeight\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ozawa | first1 = Y. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Indolepyruvate ferredoxin oxidoreductase: An oxygen-sensitive iron-sulfur enzyme from the hyperthermophilic archaeon ''Thermococcus profundus'' | url = | journal = Journal of Bioscience and Bioengineering | volume = 114 | issue = 1| pages = 23\u201327 | doi=10.1016/j.jbiosc.2012.02.014| pmid = 22608551 }}</ref>\n\n==Metabolism==\nMetabolically, ''Thermococcus'' spp. have developed a different form of glycolysis from eukaryotes and prokaryotes.<ref name=\"twentyeight\" /><ref name=\"twentynine\">{{cite journal | last1 = Zhang | first1 = Y. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Sulfur Metabolizing Microbes Dominate Microbial Communities in Andesite-Hosted Shallow-Sea Hydrothermal Systems | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0044593 | pmid = 22970260 | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 7 | issue = 9 | page=e44593| pmc = 3436782 }}</ref> One example of a metabolic pathway for these organisms is the metabolism of peptides,<ref name=\"twentyeight\" /> which occurs in three steps: first,  hydrolysis of the peptides to amino acids is  catalyzed by peptidases,<ref name=\"twentynine\" /> then the conversion of the amino acids to keto acids is catalyzed by aminotransferases,<ref name=\"twentyeight\" /> and finally CO<sub>2</sub> is released from the oxidative decarboxylation or the keto acids by four different enzymes,<ref name=\"twentynine\" /> which produces coenzyme A derivatives that are used in other important metabolic pathways.<ref name=\"twentynine\" /> ''Thermococcus'' species also have the enzyme rubisco (ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/oxygenase),<ref name=\"thirty\">{{cite journal | last1 = Davidova | first1 = I. A. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Involvement of thermophilic archaea in the biocorrosion of oil pipelines | url = | journal = Environmental Microbiology | volume = 14 | issue = 7| pages = 1762\u20131771 | doi=10.1111/j.1462-2920.2012.02721.x| pmid = 22429327 }}</ref> which is made from enzymes involved in the metabolism of nucleic acids in ''Thermococcus kodakarensis'',<ref name=\"twentyeight\" /><ref name=\"twentynine\" /><ref name=\"thirty\" /> showing how integrated these metabolic systems truly are for these hyperthermophilic microorganisms.<ref name=\"thirty\" />  Some nutrients are limiting in ''Thermococcus'' cell growth.<ref name=\"thirty\" />  Nutrients that affect cell growth the most in thermococcal species are carbon and nitrogen sources.<ref name=\"thirty\" /> Since thermococcal species do not metabolically generate all necessary amino acids, some have to be provided by the environment in which these organisms thrive. Some of these needed amino acids are leucine, isoleucine, and valine (the branched-chain amino acids).<ref name=\"thirty\" /> When ''Thermococcus'' species are supplemented with these amino acids, they can metabolize them and produce acetyl-CoA or succinyl-CoA,<ref name=\"thirty\" /> which are important precursors used in other metabolic pathways essential for cellular growth and respiration.<ref name=\"thirty\" /> With today's technology, ''Thermococcus'' members are relatively easy to grow in labs,<ref name=\"thirtyone\">{{cite journal | last1 = Duffaud | first1 = Guy D. | last2 = d'Hennezel | first2 = Olga B. | last3 = Peek | first3 = Andrew S. | last4 = Reysenbach | first4 = Anna-Louise | last5 = Kelly | first5 = Robert M. | year = 1998 | title = Isolation and Characterization of ''Thermococcus barossii'', sp. nov., a Hyperthermophilic Archaeon Isolated from a Hydrothermal Vent Flange Formation | doi = 10.1016/s0723-2020(98)80007-6 | journal = Systematic and Applied Microbiology | volume = 21 | issue = | page = 10 }}</ref> and are therefore considered model organisms for studying the physiological and molecular pathways of extremophiles.<ref name=\"thirtytwo\">{{cite journal | last1 = Petrova | first1 = T. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = ATP-dependent DNA ligase from ''Thermococcus'' sp 1519 displays a new arrangement of the OB-fold domain | url = | journal = Acta Crystallographica Section F | volume = 68 | issue = 12| pages = 1440\u20131447 | doi=10.1107/s1744309112043394| pmid = 23192021 | pmc = 3509962 }}</ref><ref name=\"thirtythree\">{{cite journal | last1 = Amend | first1 = J. P. | year = 2009 | title = A brief review of microbial geochemistry in the shallow-sea hydrothermal system of Vulcano Island (Italy) | url = | journal = Freiberg Online Geology | volume = 22 | issue = | page = 7 }}</ref> ''Thermococcus kodakarensis'' is one example of a model ''Thermococcus'' species, a microorganism in which has had its entire genome examined and replicated.<ref name=\"thirtythree\" /><ref name=\"thirtyfour\">{{cite journal | last1 = Hughes | first1 = R. C. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Inorganic pyrophosphatase crystals from ''Thermococcus thioreducens'' for X-ray and neutron diffraction | journal = Acta Crystallographica Section F | volume = 68 | issue = 12| pages = 1482\u20131487 |pmid=23192028 | doi=10.1107/S1744309112032447 | pmc=3509969}}</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\nThermococcal species can grow between 60 and 80\u00b0C, which gives them a great ecological advantage to be the first organisms to colonize new hydrothermal environments.<ref name=\"thirtyfive\">{{cite journal | last1 = Itoh | first1 = T | year = 2003 | title = Taxonomy of Nonmethanogenic Hyperthermophilic and Related Thermophilic Archaea | url = | journal = Journal of Bioscience and Bioengineering | volume = 96 | issue = 3| page = 10 | doi=10.1263/jbb.96.203}}</ref><ref name=\"twentynine\"/><ref name=\"thirtyseven\">{{cite journal | last1 = Yumani Kuba | first1 = S. I. | last2 = Yamagami | first2 = Takeshi | last3 = Tokuhara | first3 = Masahiro | last4 = Kanai | first4 = Tamotsu | last5 = Ryosuke | last6 = Daiyasu | first6 = Hiromi | last7 = Atomi | first7 = Haruyuki | last8 = Ishino | first8 = Yoshizumi | year = 2012 | title = Comparative analyses of the two proliferating cell nuclear antigens from the hyperthermophilic archaeon, ''Thermococcus kodakarensis'' | url = | journal = Genes to Cells | volume = 17 | issue = 11| pages = 923\u2013937| doi = 10.1111/gtc.12007 | pmid = 23078585 }}</ref> Some thermococcal species produce CO<sub>2</sub>, H<sub>2</sub>, and H<sub>2</sub>S as products of metabolism and respiration.<ref name=\"thirtythree\" /> The releases of these molecules are then used by other autotrophic species, aiding  the diversity of hydrothermal microbial communities.<ref name=\"twentynine\" /> This type of continuous enrichment culture plays a crucial role in the ecology of deep-sea hydrothermal vents,<ref name=\"thirtyeight\">Hakon Dahle, F. G., Marit Madsen, Nils-Kare Birkeland (2008). \"Microbial community structure analysis of produced water from a high-temperature North Sea oil-field.\" \tAntonie van Leeuwenhoek 93: 13.</ref> suggesting that thermococci interact with other organisms via metabolite exchange, which supports the growth of autotrophs.<ref name=\"twentynine\" /> ''Thermococcus'' species that release H<sub>2</sub> with the use of multiple hydrogenases (including CO-dependent hydrogenases) have been regarded as potential biocatalysts for water-gas shift reactions.<ref name=\"thirtynine\">{{cite journal | last1 = Ppyun | first1 = H. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Improved PCR performance using mutant Tpa-S DNA polymerases from the hyperthermophilic archaeon ''Thermococcus pacificus'' | url = | journal = Journal of Biotechnology | volume = 164 | issue = 2| pages = 363\u2013370 | doi=10.1016/j.jbiotec.2013.01.022| pmid = 23395617 }}</ref>\n\n==Transportation mechanisms==\n''Thermococcus'' species are naturally competent in taking up DNA and incorporating donor DNA into their genomes via homologous recombination.<ref name=\"forty\">{{cite journal | last1 = Marguet | first1 = E. |display-authors=etal | year = 2013 | title = Membrane vesicles, nanopods and/or nanotubes produced by hyperthermophilic archaea of the genus ''Thermococcus'' | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/3da45ca8f4f55cc3f6ddf32def3f558c43fc760a| journal = Biochemical Society Transactions | volume = 41 | issue = 1| pages = 436\u2013442 | doi=10.1042/bst20120293 | pmid=23356325}}</ref> These species can produce membrane vesicles (MVs),<ref name=\"forty\" /> formed by budding from the outermost cellular membranes,<ref name=\"forty\" /><ref name=\"fortyone\">{{cite journal | last1 = Gaudin | first1 = M. |display-authors=etal | year = 2013 | title = Hyperthermophilic archaea produce membrane vesicles that can transfer DNA | url = | journal = Environmental Microbiology Reports | volume = 5 | issue = 1| pages = 109\u2013116 | doi=10.1111/j.1758-2229.2012.00348.x | pmid=23757139}}</ref> which can capture and obtain plasmids from neighboring Archaea species  to transfer the DNA into either themselves or surrounding species.<ref name=\"forty\" /> These MVs are secreted from the cells in clusters, forming nanospheres or nanotubes,<ref name=\"fortyone\" /> keeping the internal membranes continuous.<ref name=\"forty\" /> \n<br>''Thermococcus'' species produce numerous MVs, transferring DNA, metabolites, and even toxins in some species;<ref name=\"fortyone\" /> moreover, these MVs protect their contents against thermodegradation by transferring these macromolecules in a protected environment.<ref name=\"forty\" /><ref name=\"fortyone\" /> MVs also prevent infections by capturing viral particles.<ref name=\"fortyone\" /> Along with transporting macromolecules, ''Thermococcus'' species use MVs to communicate to each other.<ref name=\"forty\" /> Furthermore, these MVs are used by a specific species (''Thermococcus coalescens'') to indicate when aggregation should occur,<ref name=\"forty\" /> so these typically single-celled miroorganisms can fuse into one massive single cell.<ref name=\"forty\" />\n<br>It has been reported that ''Thermococcus kodakarensis'' has four virus-like integrated gene elements containing subtilisin-like serine protease precursors.<ref name=\"fortytwo\">{{cite journal | last1 = Li | first1 = Z. |display-authors=etal | year = 2013 | title = ''Thermococcus kodakarensis'' DNA replication | url = | journal = Biochemical Society Transactions | volume = 41 | issue = 1| pages = 332\u2013338 | doi=10.1042/bst20120303| pmid = 23356307 }}</ref> To date, only two viruses have been isolated from ''Thermococcus'' spp., PAVE1 and TPV1.<ref name=\"fortytwo\" /> These viruses exist in their hosts in a carrier state.<ref name=\"fortytwo\" />  \n<br>The process of DNA replication and elongation has been extensively studied in ''T. kodakarensis''.<ref name=\"fortytwo\" /> The DNA molecule is a circular structure consisting of about 2 million base pairs in length, and has more than 2,000 sequences that code for proteins.<ref name=\"fortytwo\" />\n\n==Future technology==\nAn enzyme from ''Thermococcus'', Tpa-S DNA polymerase, has been found to be more efficient in long and rapid PCR than Taq-polymerase.<ref name=\"fortythree\">{{cite journal | last1 = Azumi Hirata | first1 = Y. H. | last2 = Okada | first2 = Jun | last3 = Sakudo | first3 = Akikazu | last4 = Ikuta | first4 = Kazuyoshi | last5 = Kanaya | first5 = Shigenori | last6 = Takano | first6 = Kazufumi | year = 2013 | title = Enzymatic activity of a subtilisin homolog, Tk-SP, from ''Thermococcus kodakarensis'' in detergents and its ability to degrade the abnormal prion protein | url = | journal = BMC Biotechnology | volume = 13 | issue = | page = 7 }}</ref> Tk-SP, another enzyme from ''T. kodakarensis'',<ref name=\"fortythree\" /><ref name=\"fortyfour\">{{cite journal | last1 = Trofimov | first1 = A. A. |display-authors=etal | year = 2012 | title = Influence of intermolecular contacts on the structure of recombinant prolidase from ''Thermococcus sibiricus'' | url = | journal = Acta Crystallographica Section F | volume = 68 | issue = 11| pages = 1275\u20131278 | doi=10.1107/s174430911203761x| pmid = 23143231 | pmc = 3515363 }}</ref> can degrade abnormal prion proteins (PrPSc);<ref name=\"fortythree\" /> prions are misfolded proteins that can cause fatal diseases in all organisms.<ref name=\"fortythree\" /> Tk-SP shows broad substrate specificity, and degraded prions exponentially in the lab setting.<ref name=\"fortythree\" /> This enzyme does not require calcium or any other substrate to fold, so is showing great potential in studies thus far.<ref name=\"fortythree\" />  Additional studies have been coordinated on the phosphoserine phosphatase (PSP) enzyme of ''T. onnurineus'', which provided an essential component in the regulation of PSP activity.<ref name=\"fortyfour\" /> This information is useful for drug companies, because abnormal PSP activity leads to a major decrease in serine levels of the nervous system, causing neurological diseases and complications.<ref name=\"fortyfour\" />\n<br>''Thermococcus'' spp. can increase gold mining efficiency up to 95% due to their specific abilities in bioleaching.<ref name=\"fortyfive\">{{cite journal | last1 = Muhammad Nisar | first1 = N. R. | last2 = Bashir | first2 = Qamar | last3 = Gardener | first3 = Qurra-tul-Ann | last4 = Shafiq | first4 = Muhammad | last5 = Akhtar | first5 = Muhammad | year = 2013 | title = TK 1299, a highly thermostable NAD(P)H oxidase from ''Thermococcus kodakaraensis'' exhibiting higher enzymatic activity with NADPH | url = | journal = Journal of Bioscience and Bioengineering | volume = 116 | issue = 1| pages = 39\u201344 | doi=10.1016/j.jbiosc.2013.01.020| pmid = 23453203 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n<!-- ===Scientific journals===\n -->\n* {{ cite journal | author = Judicial Commission of the International Committee on Systematics of Prokaryotes | date = 2005 | title = The nomenclatural types of the orders Acholeplasmatales, Halanaerobiales, Halobacteriales, Methanobacteriales, Methanococcales, Methanomicrobiales, Planctomycetales, Prochlorales, Sulfolobales, Thermococcales, Thermoproteales and Verrucomicrobiales are the genera ''Acholeplasma'', ''Halanaerobium'', ''Halobacterium'', ''Methanobacterium'', ''Methanococcus'', ''Methanomicrobium'', ''Planctomyces'', ''Prochloron'', ''Sulfolobus'', ''Thermococcus'', ''Thermoproteus'' and ''Verrucomicrobium'', respectively. Opinion 79 | journal =  Int. J. Syst. Evol. Microbiol.  | volume =  55 | pages = 517\u2013518 | pmid = 15653928 | issue = Pt 1 | doi = 10.1099/ijs.0.63548-0| doi-access = free }}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Mora|first1=Maximilian|last2=Bellack|first2=Annett|last3=Ugele|first3=Matthias|last4=Hopf|first4=Johann|last5=Wirth|first5=Reinhard|title=The Temperature Gradient-Forming Device, an Accessory Unit for Normal Light Microscopes To Study the Biology of Hyperthermophilic Microorganisms|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|date=August 2014|volume=80|issue=15|pages=4764\u201370|doi=10.1128/AEM.00984-14|pmid=24858087|pmc=4148812}}<!--|accessdate=14 November 2014-->\n* {{ cite journal | display-authors =3 | author = Zillig W | author2 = Holz I | author3 = Klenk HP | author4 =  Trent J | author5 = Wunderl S | author6 = Janekovic D | author7 = Imsel E | author8 = Haas B | date = 1987 | title = Pyrococcus woesei, sp. nov., an ultra-thermophilic marine Archaebacterium, representing a novel order, Thermococcales | journal =  Syst. Appl. Microbiol.  | volume =  9 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 62\u201370 | doi=10.1016/S0723-2020(87)80057-7}}\n* {{ cite journal | author = Zillig W | author2 = Holz L | author3 = Janekovic 